From f3264f7c77a2c48a0366c65313a188a8e02a7edc Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Sage Builder <bc230212964ssh@vu.edu.pk>
Date: Wed, 22 Jul 2026 21:40:46 +0500
Subject: [PATCH 06/16] feat(deputy): bind autopay to the evaluated policy
 identity
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Approval for an autopay was keyed on the model STRING alone, so a change to the payout
prompt or the money-path parser silently inherited a model's old approval — a combination
that was never re-evaluated could still auto-pay. This binds autopay to the full POLICY
IDENTITY: provider host + actual canonical model + payout prompt version + money-parser
version, all stamped on the brief that produced the decision.

  - brain-core: PAYOUT_PROMPT_VERSION (versions SYSTEM_PROMPT); promptVersion/parserVersion
    added to DecisionBrief + StoredBrief (persisted in the json blob — no DB migration).
  - brain: PARSER_POLICY_VERSION (versions the callProvider money parse); callProvider
    stamps both onto every fresh LLM brief (hardenBrief spreads them through).
  - decisions: persist + reconstruct the two versions; legacy rows reconstruct as null →
    the gate holds them for review (safe, subtract-only).
  - model-policy: APPROVED_IDENTITIES pins the EXACT (provider, model, prompt, parser)
    combinations that passed the promotion battery; judgeIdentityGate replaces the
    model-only gate. A fallback model, a different provider, or a BUMPED prompt/parser
    version all fall to manual review — even at pay/1.0.
  - pipeline: the b2 gate now checks identity; the held reason records the full identity.
  - judge-eval single-sources JUDGE_PROMPT_VERSION from PAYOUT_PROMPT_VERSION.

The deployed prod combination (gemini-flash-lite @ commonstack, payout-v1, payout-parse-v1)
is approved, so there is no behavior change for it. This only ever turns a would-pay into
a review; it can never cause a wrong payout. Not deployed, not enforced beyond the existing
(off-by-default) autopay path.

