From e539018e7ba081d7a8103da367e214e4853f6fcf Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Sage Builder <bc230212964ssh@vu.edu.pk>
Date: Wed, 22 Jul 2026 22:37:54 +0500
Subject: [PATCH 09/16] fix(deputy): harden the evidence renderer against
 redirect SSRF and oversized text
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Real-browser tests surfaced a redirect SSRF in the rendered-evidence capture: the request
guard fired only for each request the browser INITIATED, but a server-side 3xx was followed
by the browser WITHOUT re-firing the route handler — so a public, guard-passing evidence URL
could 302 the headless browser into a PRIVATE host (cloud metadata at 169.254.169.254, an
internal service) and its body would be captured into the evidence text. Proven with a
loopback fixture: the handler saw only the entry, yet the browser fetched the internal
origin and captured "INTERNAL SECRET DATA".

The route handler now follows redirects MANUALLY with maxRedirects:0, re-validating every
hop's Location against the same requestGuard + public-DNS check before fetching it (chains
included, capped at 6 hops); a private target is aborted before any connection, and an
unresolved/over-long chain is refused rather than handed to the browser to follow. Legitimate
public→public redirects still resolve.

Also: cap captured innerText at MAX_TEXT_CHARS (100k) IN-PAGE before it crosses the CDP
bridge, so a hostile page can't stream megabytes into our process or the judge. And a
test-only RenderTestHooks.allowOrigins — not reachable through any production config or env
(prod calls renderEvidence(url) with no hooks) — lets an integration test serve fixtures on
loopback without weakening the production guard; only the exact listed origins bypass it, and
a different loopback port still goes through the unmodified guard.

The renderer remains off/shadow by default; RENDERED_EVIDENCE_MODE=enforce stays prohibited.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
